WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:04.000
Hi, I'm Sarah Altman and I'm on the Developer Relations team at Posit.

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:09.600
Today I'm going to talk to you about brand.yml, a really exciting new project from the Shiny

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:16.559
and Quarto team. Brand.yml allows you to easily apply branding across reports, dashboards,

00:00:16.559 --> 00:00:23.600
apps, and more with a single yml file. There will be a live Q&A after this presentation

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:28.320
where we'll be joined by Gareth Aiden-Bouy and Carlo Scheidegger, two of the software

00:00:28.320 --> 00:00:33.279
engineers who created brand.yml. We're all really excited about this project and are

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:40.000
looking forward to your question. So today I'm going to show you how to transform your

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:45.919
unbranded Quarto documents and Shiny apps that might look something like this into consistent

00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:52.560
branded products like this, all with a single yml file. We'll talk about why you might want

00:00:52.560 --> 00:01:00.080
to use brand.yml, the structure of a brand.yml file, how to apply brand.yml to Quarto documents

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:06.879
and Shiny apps, and how to create a brand.yml with the help of an LLM. So why use brand.yml?

00:01:07.519 --> 00:01:13.839
Let's say you're a data person in an organization and as part of your job you create reports,

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:20.160
apps, plots, dashboards, and other things. All these artifacts that people at your organization

00:01:20.239 --> 00:01:26.320
and maybe even people outside of your organization use. And your company has particular branding,

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:32.800
it has colors, logos, fonts that it uses in its materials. That branding might even be

00:01:32.800 --> 00:01:41.279
immediately recognizable to people outside of your company. So you as a diligent data professional

00:01:41.279 --> 00:01:46.080
try to apply your company's branding across all your plots and dashboards and apps.

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:53.279
But you run into a couple of hurdles. First, you know how to change the color of your plots

00:01:53.279 --> 00:01:57.360
and you know how to adapt the theme of your Quarto dashboards. But to really get your company's

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:01.839
branding right, you need to play around with CSS and other things that are mostly outside

00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:07.279
of your toolbox. Second, you can get some of the branding right but at the same time your

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:11.279
co-workers are also trying to apply the same branding guidelines and you're all kind of

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:15.360
getting it right but in different ways. And so your work as a team doesn't really feel right.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:20.960
It doesn't feel consistent. And then maybe you've amassed all this code that brands your outputs

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:26.320
and it looks really nice, but then the company decides to change its brand. And so now you have

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:31.600
to comb back through your code and update everything manually. A frustrating and time-intensive task.

00:02:32.559 --> 00:02:34.479
So you have a couple problems that you need to solve.

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:42.399
Consistent branding across not only your own work but across your teams ensures your work

00:02:42.399 --> 00:02:47.039
looks professional and polished. Branding can be a subtle but really powerful way

00:02:47.039 --> 00:02:53.600
to make your work shine. And your organization might also require you to follow brand guidelines.

00:02:53.600 --> 00:03:00.800
So you need branding but branding consistently can be difficult. Your brand guidelines might

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:06.240
include detailed requirements and applying various colors, fonts, and logos across tools

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.960
and programming languages requires a lot of manual effort that can be prone to error.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:17.520
It can also be really difficult to update branding consistently when brand guidelines change.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:20.800
Think about all the files you might need to update with traditional approaches.

00:03:23.759 --> 00:03:28.720
Finally, ensuring team consistency can be hard. You want to make sure all contributors follow

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:34.399
brand guidelines in a similar way across all their reports and dashboards and apps,

00:03:34.399 --> 00:03:40.399
which can definitely be challenging. So addressing these problems is exactly why the team

00:03:40.399 --> 00:03:46.399
behind brand.yaml created it. With brand.yaml you can define your organization's branding

00:03:46.399 --> 00:03:52.559
in a single yaml file and apply that branding across reports, dashboards, and apps pretty much

00:03:52.559 --> 00:04:00.800
instantly. So what does this mean? It means we write a single yaml file that specifies colors,

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:07.520
logos, fonts, and typographic choices. You're going to often see this named underscore brand.yaml.

00:04:10.399 --> 00:04:15.440
Then you can instantly apply branding from that yaml file across quarter documents,

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:20.160
shiny apps, and more. So at this point you might have a couple of questions.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:28.160
How do we structure this yaml file? And after we've created the yaml file, how do we actually

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:34.239
apply it to our outputs to brand them? So let's look at the yaml file structure first.

00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:38.880
So I'm going to give you an overview of the file structure and explain how you'd go about

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:44.480
building up your own brand.yaml file. But if this seems like a lot of manual work, know that towards

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:49.920
the end of this presentation I'll show you how to create a brand.yaml with the help of an LLM.

00:04:50.799 --> 00:04:56.799
So yaml is a language often used to represent structured data in a human-readable format.

00:04:56.799 --> 00:05:02.239
You often see yaml used for things like configuration files. You don't need to know

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:08.399
a lot about yaml to get started creating yaml files like brand.yaml.

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:16.480
One thing to know is that yaml uses key-value pairs. So the key in this case right here is

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:21.679
meta and then this whole thing is the value. And we have another key-value pair within that.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:28.239
And that's all you really need to know about how yaml works. So now let's talk about the specifics

00:05:28.239 --> 00:05:37.359
of a brand.yaml file. Brand.yaml files require a particular format to brand your outputs like

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:46.640
Shiny apps and Cordo documents. There are four main components. Meta, which contains identity

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:55.040
information like the name of your company. Logo, which is where you specify files or links to your

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:01.839
brand's logo at various sizes. Color, which is where you define the colors in your brand's color

00:06:01.839 --> 00:06:08.880
palette and how those colors are used. And typography, which is where you define fonts

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:18.640
and other typographic choices. So again a brand.yaml file will need meta, logo, color, typography.

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:25.600
You can also specify defaults, which is where you can add additional context-specific settings

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:29.839
that might be options used by like Bootstrap in Cordo or Shiny.

00:06:31.679 --> 00:06:39.040
So let's take a closer look at the color and typography sections. So first, color. So the

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:45.920
color section in brand.yaml consists of two main parts. There's palette, which is a set of named

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:51.920
colors specific to your brand. So in this case, the key value pairs are a name of a color,

00:06:52.480 --> 00:06:56.959
which this could be anything you want, and then the hex code for that color.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:08.399
So this brand defines a black, blue, neutral, red, and violet. The second part is the theme colors.

00:07:09.359 --> 00:07:16.079
And this is where you assign those specific colors to various UI elements. So here we're saying

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:24.079
we want to use our neutral color for background. So if you were building up this file from scratch,

00:07:24.079 --> 00:07:28.880
you would first want to define the colors in your palette by taking a look at your

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:35.279
brand guidelines and figure out what colors are in your brand's color palette to define those colors

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.920
and then map those brand colors to particular UI elements. How do you want those colors

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:47.679
to be used? Where do you want them to appear? Okay, so now typography.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:55.519
Like color, typography has two sections. First, you define the fonts used by your brand.

00:07:57.519 --> 00:08:03.600
And you can specify either local or online font sources. So this brand.yaml uses Google fonts.

00:08:05.359 --> 00:08:12.320
Then you take those fonts and define how they are used by different typographic elements.

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:18.559
So in this case, we're using this font as the base font. And then for headings, we're using

00:08:18.559 --> 00:08:25.679
Montserrat with a particular weight and also assigning a color. Great. So, so far,

00:08:25.679 --> 00:08:30.480
we've talked about why you might want to use brand.yaml, how to structure a brand file.

